t 1991 after the failed Soviet coup attempt, as one of the first countries to do so. The Soviet Union recognised the independence of Estonia on 6 September. Estonia's ties with Boris Yeltsin weakened since the Russian leader's initial show of solidarity with the Baltic states in January 1991. Issues surrounding the withdrawal of Russian troops from the Baltic republics and Estonia's denial of automatic citizenship to persons who settled in Estonia in 1941-1991 and offspring ranked high on the list of points of contention.\n\n-valign=\"top\"\n2009\nBoth countries established diplomatic relations on September 23, 2009. \n\n-valign=\"top\"\n2009\nBoth countries established diplomatic relations on January 23, 2009. \n-valign=\"top\"\n\nBULLET::::- Estonia is represented in Serbia through a non-resident ambassador based in Tallinn (in the Foreign Ministry).\nBULLET::::- Serbia is represented in Estonia through its embassy in Helsinki (Finland).\nBULLET::::- Estonian Ministry of Foreign Affairs about relations with Serbia\nBULLET::::- Serbian Ministry of Foreign Affairs about relations with Estonia\n-valign=\"top\"\n\nBULLET::::- Estonia recognised Slovakia on 15 January 1993.\nBULLET::::- Estonia is represented in Slovakia through its embassy in Vienna (Austria).\nBULLET::::- Slovakia is represented in Estonia through its embassy in Riga (Latvia) and an honorary consulate in Tallinn.\nBULLET::::- Both countries are full members of NATO and of the European Union.\nBULLET::::- Estonian Ministry of Foreign Affairs about relations with Slovakia\n-valign=\"top\"\n\nBULLET::::- The establishment of diplomatic relations between the Republic of Estonia and the Republic of Korea began on 1991-09-17.\nBULLET::::- The Republic of Estonia has an honorary consulate in Seoul.\nBULLET::::- The Republic of Korea is represented in the Republic of Estonia through its embassy in Helsinki, Finland and through an honorary consulate in Tallinn.\nBULLET::::- In 2006 South Korea was ranked as E